That's a very practical question when setting up a new Rust project!When working on a Rust backend (or any Rust project), you generally want to ignore the files and directories that are automatically generated by the compiler (rustc) and the build tool (cargo). These files are not part of your source code and can be easily recreated.The core of what you should ignore is handled by a .gitignore file.🗑️ Files and Directories to IgnoreThe single most important directory to ignore in any Rust project is target/.Directory/FileWhy You Should Ignore Ittarget/This is where Cargo puts all of the compiled results, including the executable binaries, object files, and build metadata. This content is platform-specific and changes frequently, making it unnecessary to track in version control.Cargo.lockThis file records the exact versions of all dependencies used to build your project. Note: While it is essential to track this file for applications (like a backend), it should generally be ignored for library crates to give users flexibility. For a backend service, though, you should usually commit this file.VS Code or IDE filesFiles like .vscode/, .idea/, or .DS_Store are specific to your local setup and should not be shared.📝 The Standard Rust .gitignoreThe best practice is to start with the standard Rust .gitignore template. You can create a file named .gitignore in the root directory of your project (where your Cargo.toml is located) with the following content:Code snippet# Generated files
/target/

# Rust-specific files
# Rust language server (RLS) and analysis files
/Cargo.lock # Usually committed for applications, ignored for libraries
# Uncomment the line below if you are building a library that
# you expect others to include, otherwise, commit Cargo.lock
# Cargo.lock

# Operating System Files
.DS_Store

# IDE/Editor Files
.vscode/
.idea/

# Rust binary cache
# Only necessary if you run 'cargo install' from within your project
.cargo/

# Build artifacts for C/C++ dependencies
# (If your project uses C/C++ crates like "cc" or "bindgen")
# out/
